---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const title = 'BEM vs LSCSS';
const description = 'Compare BEM and Layered Semantic CSS for naming, architecture, modifiers, state handling, scalability, and long-term maintainability.';

const bemExample = `.product-card {}
.product-card__title {}
.product-card__price {}
.product-card--featured {}`;

const lscssExample = `.product-card {}
.product-card > .title {}
.product-card > .price {}
.product-card--featured {}`;

const stateExample = `.product-card--featured.is_loading {}
.product-card.has_error {}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            BEM vs LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            BEM helped solve real problems. It gave teams structure when CSS was
            mostly organised by panic, inheritance accidents, and selectors that
            behaved like loose cables in a server room.
        </p>

        <p>
            LSCSS keeps some of that discipline, especially explicit component
            variants, but removes much of the naming ceremony. It relies more on
            cascade layers, short scoped child selectors, design tokens, and
            explicit state classes.
        </p>

        <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="BEM and LSCSS comparison sections">
            <a href="#main-differences">Differences</a>
            <a href="#naming">Naming</a>
            <a href="#modifiers">Modifiers</a>
            <a href="#state">State</a>
            <a href="#when-to-use">When to use</a>
        </nav>

        <section id="main-differences" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Main differences
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>BEM uses explicit <code>block__element--modifier</code> naming.</li>
                <li>LSCSS uses semantic component names with short contextual child selectors.</li>
                <li>BEM encodes structure into class names.</li>
                <li>LSCSS usually keeps structure in the selector and markup hierarchy.</li>
                <li>BEM depends heavily on naming discipline.</li>
                <li>LSCSS combines naming discipline with cascade layers, tokens, and modern CSS.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="naming" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Element naming
            </h2>

            <p>
                BEM makes ownership clear by repeating the block name in every
                element class.
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={bemExample} />

            <p>
                LSCSS usually keeps child names short and lets the parent
                component provide context.
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={lscssExample} />

            <p>
                This borrows from RSCSS-style selectors. The aim is readable
                markup without losing component ownership.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="modifiers" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Modifiers
            </h2>

            <p>
                LSCSS keeps the useful BEM idea of explicit modifiers for
                reusable component variants. A modifier should describe a stable
                version of a component, not a temporary interaction state.
            </p>

            <p>
                This is one of the areas where BEM still gives LSCSS a useful
                foundation.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="state" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                State and conditions
            </h2>

            <p>
                LSCSS separates modifiers from state and condition classes.
                A featured card and a loading card are not the same kind of
                information.
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={stateExample} />

            <p>
                Use <code>.is_*</code> for temporary state and <code>.has_*</code>
                for conditions or content presence. This keeps behaviour easier
                to read and easier to manage from JavaScript.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="when-to-use" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                When BEM works well
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>large teams needing strict naming consistency</li>
                <li>older codebases without cascade layers or modern CSS support</li>
                <li>projects where explicit naming reduces onboarding risk</li>
                <li>systems where every element must be identifiable from its class alone</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>
                When LSCSS helps more
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>modern front-end teams using cascade layers and tokens</li>
                <li>projects focused on readable HTML and lower naming noise</li>
                <li>systems where state, theme, and legacy CSS need clear separation</li>
                <li>teams that want structure without turning every class into a family tree</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Recommended reading
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li><a href="/naming/">Naming</a></li>
                <li><a href="/modifiers-and-state/">Modifiers and state</a></li>
                <li><a href="/layers/">Layers</a></li>
                <li><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <p>
            BEM is not wrong. It solved real problems. LSCSS takes the useful
            parts, removes some verbosity, and adds more protection through
            layers, tokens, state naming, and modern CSS.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
